title: U2 Practice: Charge Balance
description:
This quiz covers generating charge balance equations from a list of ions in a solution.

The format of the charge balance equation should be "[Cations]=[Anions]", following the following example (sulfuric acid) for formatting formulas and multiple charges:

[H+]=[OH-]+[HSO4-]+2[SO42-]

Note that there are no spaces in the answer.

title: U2 Practice: Complex Ions
description: This practice quiz covers calculation of concentrations of complex ions given formation constants.

title: U2 Practice: Ionic Strength
description: This practice quiz covers calculating ionic strength of a solution.

title: U2 Practice: Mass Balance
description:
This practice quiz covers generating a mass balance equation for weak acids and bases.

The answer below is for a 0.50 M solution of sulfuric acid and shows the expected formatting:

0.50=[H2SO4]+[HSO4-]+[SO4--]

title: U2 Practice: Polyprotic acid/base

title: U2 Practice: Reaction Quotient
description:
This practice quiz covers writing the reaction quotient Q

 

Follow the following conventions for formatting your answer:

  • Use multiple + or - signs for multiple charged ions: sulfate as SO4--
  • Brackets for concentrations
  • single '/' between product and reactant terms

Q = [TiCl4]/[Ti++++][Cl-]^4

title: U2 Practice: Separation of Ions
description:
This practice quiz covers determining which ion will precipitate from a solution first, and calculating separation efficiency for precipitation separations.

Enter ion formulas with the appropriate number of charges:
Ag+
Ca++
Al+++

title: U2 Practice: Solubility Product
description: This practice quiz covers calculating solubility from Ksp.

title: U2 Practice: Strong acid/base
description: This practice quiz covers calculating pH of solutions of strong acids and bases, under conditions where the autoprotolysis of water either can or can not be ignored.

title: U3 Practice: Balancing Redox Half Reactions
description:
This practice quiz covers balancing redox half reactions.

In your answer:

  • separate reactants from products with " = " (include spaces)
  • separate compounds on each side of the reaction with " + " (include spaces)
  • do not include spaces between stoichiometric coefficients, formulas, charge, or phases. E.g.:
    • two sulfates is 2SO4--
    • two liquid bromines is 2Br2(l)

 

Example:

Should be expressed as: NpO3+ + 2H+ + e- = NpO2++ + H2O
